Gary Danko...you still got it & we still want it!! We've been four times & the food is always consistently decadent, delightful & delish! And the service is always top notch! Probably SF's most affordable higher end Michellin rated restaurant that we'll keep coming back to again & again (& we have)....& yes...I think I will always order the Lobster Risotto because it always results in a foodgasm! Gary Danko makes me try new things too! I don't eat fish really but I've loved two of their amuse bouches that were fish & I tried some of my bf's foie gras last nite, which I've been afraid of, but it was so tasty! Forgive all the exclamation points, but it's Gary Danko for crying out loud, so it's much deserved! =)

This place has pretty good service, but they're supposed to. I thought the food and service at Manresa were better. Here are my main points: 1) GOOD PLACE FOR BIRTHDAY Making the reservation was pleasant and they called to confirm, which I liked. I told them it was a birthday and they provided a complimentary chilled lemon mousse cake with a candle, which I liked more than the baked chocolate souffle (BTW, which is overrated on yelp). Our souffle had cooler than room temp white and dark chocolate poured in it which made it taste gross in our already soggy and old souffle. It was not impressive at all. 2) SEATING PROBLEM I really hated the seats and table we were given. So to clear room for people walking by, they cleared one side of the table so it has no chairs and the two people have to sit against the wall, as if you're facing a firing squad. Another Asian couple were seated next to us and I really did not like that since everyone else got normal seats facing each other. Also, the girl next to me kept on making the shared seat along the wall move. Also, people working there kept running into our champagne holder and banging it against our table during dinner, which totally pissed me off! I really hated these seats. They should just get rid of them. 3) FOOD - PRESENTATION AND TASTE MEDIOCRE The first taste, I forgot what it was, but it was obviously not memorable. The lobster risotto was too temperature hot, but the glazed oysters and caviar were great. The shellfish with thai red curry and jasmine rice was not great and the lobster with butternut squash and rock shrimp was mushy and tasted weird. However, my lemon peppered duck, duck hash and puree was really good. The steak was ok. I really liked the cheese dish, but overall, seemed like they were in a hurry to get us out of there. I didn't like feeling rushed. They totally rushed us the beginning of the meal until the cheese plate. I really hated that. What exacerbated the situation was being seated at that awful location seeing each and every dish and waiter go back and forth. It was really tacky of them to put seats there. I really hated the experience of sitting there and felt bad sticking my six foot one inch boyfriend in the corner (I'm left handed). Also, the bite-sized desserts on the doily was really unthoughtfully presented. The doily was oily as expected and a bakery would've had a better presentation. They should place them on ceramic plates like they do at Chez TJ or Manresa instead of on a stinky doily. I will probably never come here again because I know that I'd get better service, not be rushed and better seats at Chez TJ or Manresa and there are other restaurants I want to try.

We flew into SF for my husband's and son's birthday. I planned a weekend of activities and hoped to get Gary Danko, but they were booked. We lucked out while at our friend's house for Thanksgiving as a 9pm reservation became available for that Saturday. I booked and later added the special occasion info on Saturday afternoon. I actually think the price was a good deal for the quality of the food. We ordered seared foie gras, seared scallops, lobster with mash potatoes, seafood curry, lemon duck breast, steak filet, chocolate soufflé, and ice cream macaroons. Everything was good. The dishes I probably wouldn't order again as they didn't stand out to me were the seared foie gras (served without toast; we prefer a fruit sauce with toast without the caramelized onions; but the quality of the foie gras itself was very good), the seared scallops (nothing you can't get elsewhere), and the duck (tender but I prefer a crispier skin; the flavor reminded me a little of Thanksgiving turkey and stuffing). The dishes we really liked that were more extraordinary were the lobster and mash potato and the seafood curry (doesn't taste at all like Asian curry; just a light creamy taste). The chocolate soufflé (very light in our case unlike another review) which we added vanilla ice cream to was the best I've ever had. Our down to earth server (aware of asking me if I wanted to exclude the blue cheese butter for my 7yo daughter's filet) was excellent. The auxiliary staff were a bit unfriendly (no smiles even) and stuffy...probably because we brought our 2 kids. Except for making us feel a little like we were in a Pretty Woman movie because of our kids (we eat in fine dining restaurants enough where my kids love foie gras and can distinguish the difference between different qualities of steak), we enjoyed our dining experience and would return the next time we are in town. However, I was a bit sad that they didn't do anything special for my husband and son's birthdays, but I left it alone especially since we had a lot of sweets already and felt awkward to ask in front of them.

Fantastic Restaurant. But be warned: YOU MAY NEED TO MAKE RESERVATION TWO MONTHS IN ADVANCE. Also, I had the least expensive meal of the night at $175.00. First off, gotta give credit to the BF for planning our anniversary dinner here :p GD has such a fun menu concept. They give you the options of 3,4, or 5 Prix fixe courses, where you can choose any dish off their menu; doesnt have to be 1 app, 1 entree or 1 dessert so of course I chose to get mostly savory dishes and we shared 1 dessert. Every dish was exquisite in taste and presentation. -Crispy Egg: The egg had crispy crumbs on the outside, perfectly soft boiled on the inside. The yolk melted into the grits, mushrooms, and arugula. -Bass w/ Gnocchi: One of my favorites! The fish was cooked crunchy on the outside and the meat was moist and flaky. It was accompanied by fluffy gnocchi in a refreshing arugula pesto and other interesting sauces that just melded together perfectly. - Lamb loin: Served atop red bell pepper, eggplant, and zucchini (reminiscent of ratatouille) Mild lamb flavor but tender throughout. -Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Black Trumpet Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon: Lobster has never tasted this good. The texture of the lobster was close to melt in your mouth and the meat was sweet and fresh beyond words! Finished our meal off with the baked chocolate souffle, which was light an fluffy. The sauces melded well with the souffle and the entire dish wasn't too sweet. They decorated the dish to say Happy Anniversary and offered to take a picture for us. They sent us home with an upside down pineapple cake and that was the end of our perfect meal. Thank you Gary Danko!

Can't wait to return and have their foie gras, scallops and lobster.

One of the most enjoyable dining experiences I've ever had. I got a reservation for my parents and I to celebrate my mother's birthday. I called 2 months in advance to get a 6pm reservation time on a Monday. If you want to get a more "dinner" dining time, then I suggest calling right when you can start making reservations, which is two months prior. The first time I called, I was only offered a 9pm time slot. For the food: the portions here are huge for a tasting menu! We each got the 4-course. I was debating between 4 vs. 5 courses and I am so glad that I chose the 4-course. Be aware that the food is very, very rich. You will leave feeling stuffed. I will be honest in saying that nothing about the food is revolutionary -- there's no innovative pairing of flavors or ingredients. The food is more of "classic" fine dining, meaning that you should not expect molecular gastronomy types of things; it's more of meat and potatoes, fish, and cream sauces (hence the heavy feeling after). However, all of it is prepared very well. Service is also excellent here. Water is always refilled, and the waitstaff is attentive at just the right moments. All the little details are attended to, and there is no judgment about how many courses you decide to order. Overpriced? Definitely. This isn't a place that you come to for a great value. But, solid food + excellent service makes this a place that should be visited to celebrate a special occasion. Tip: not everyone at the table has to order the same amount of courses. This was something that I was wondering about as I was reading up on this place! Also, valet is the cheapest option ($12, I believe), unless you're lucky enough to find street parking. It's right next Ghiradelli square.

Gary Danko, how are you rated the best restaurant in SF by Yelpers?! I've been to Manresa, Saison, Coi, Benu, Meadowood, Keiko a Nob Hill, Cyrus, Quince, Boulevard, Commis, the list goes on and on...but this meal by far was the most uninteresting. What shocked us the minute we were seated at the table was how crowded it felt inside. The over sized cheese cart kept bumping into my friend's chair during dinner. You would expect a restaurant of this caliber to give their guests more privacy and space. The food was lacking in character, creativity and quality. The scallop risotto was average. The steak was dry and not very flavorful. Harris' Restaurant definitely has better quality meats. Some of the dishes were too salty. The cheese course which is usually extra was marginal. They didn't have a good cheese selection as compared to other high end restaurants. It was abundant but not exciting. I felt sorry for our server because he sounded like a broken record trying to recite the two dozen or so cheese options on the cart. That's a tough job. The cart was sitting in the room for most of the evening. Some of the cheeses tasted lukewarm and softer than normal. The wine pairing wasn't necessary. I didn't think it enhanced the food. Or maybe the food didn't compliment the wine. I'm going to go out on a limb to say the wine was better than the food that evening. In terms of pricing, it is one of the more reasonable tasting menus offered in the Bay Area. You definitely feel full after you leave the restaurant. I can understand why a lot of men like this place. They can make their dates happy and also feel like they're not eating foam. I feel like Gary Danko caters to diners who enjoy quantity of portions, flexibility with course selection and good service. Yes, the service was the star of the evening. We enjoyed the experience because our servers were attentive and excellent. I won't be returning unless someone special requests a meal there. I have several friends who love it there. I guess it's hard to please everyone all the time.

    I have been dying to try the raved about SF institution that is Gary Danko for so long.  Thanks boyfriend for treating me here!  We almost didn't make it to celebrate our Anniversary.  So, I told him that I wanted to go here like three months prior; GD only takes reservations two months in advance.  I forgot to remind him at the two month mark.  I took it upon myself to call when I remembered at the one month mark; they were completely booked.  I complained to bf, and he called them to double check though.  An hour later he got a call saying someone had canceled and we got a reservation on 12/5 at 6pm.  Of course I was ecstatic how lucky we were!  Upon arrival, service was impeccable.  Our coats were taken off/put on us, water was constantly filled and bread was constantly put on our plates whenever it was empty, all without notifying the waitstaff, utensils were constantly changed, napkins were folded when away from the table.  A girl can definitely get used to this fine dining treatment!

    Compliments of the chef we were presented with a salmon and crab breaded ball with a hummus sauce.  This was a delicious start to a foodgasmic meal!  I don't even like fish and I could have eaten a couple of these delectable morsels!  I chose the 3-course meal & he chose the 4.  We also enjoyed our finely crafted cocktails.  For our appetizer we both chose the Risotto with Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms and Butternut Squash.  It was so creamy without being overly rich, it was very filling and the portion was generous.  It definitely made up for the years of risotto absence that I've endured.  For his mains he chose the Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon, as well as the Roasted Pork Belly and Tenderloin with Brussels Sprouts, Bacon, Parsnip Purée and Maple-Cider Glaze.  I'll admit I can be iffy with seafood, because frankly, some places where I've had it, make it taste, well fishy, not here.  The lobster was amazing & was like butter melting in our mouths.  We also enjoyed the potato puree along side it.  His pork tenderloin was so moist & could easily be cut with a butter knife!  The pork belly was delicious too oozing in our mouths, but he loved the tenderloin.  For my main I chose the Seared Filet of Beef with Leeks, Crimini Mushrooms, Braised Shallots and Potato Cake.  The beef was a nice portion done medium rare (as requested) & the mushrooms and leeks and shallots made for a sweet accompanying sauce.  The beef was moist and tender and I also enjoyed the breaded potato cake.  For my dessert I chose the much talked about Chocolate Souffle with the Bittersweet Chocolate Sauce & Creme Anglaise.  This was perfect, not too sweet but not bitter, and light as air.  His dessert was the Crème Fraîche Cheesecake with Cranberries and Caramelized Pecans.  He enjoyed his cheesecake & the accompanying berry sorbet as well (we couldn't put our finger on what fruit it was).  Also presented to us was a delicious Passion fruit mousse cake compliments of the chef for our anniversary as well as assorted cookies.  We ate up the mousse cake, especially me, since I love passion fruit.  He did nibble on one of the brownies from the cookies while I refrained & took the rest home because I was about to explode!  All tables were also given a pumpkin morning pastry to take home to enjoy.  

    I can't wait to come back for another exquisite DINING EXPERIENCE at Gary Danko.  It truly is an experience with the minimum two hours of fine food and fine service you will have the pleasure of experiencing here.  

    TIPS: There are actually two immaculate bathrooms here, one in the back and one in the front.  And maybe you didn't need to know this, but I pointed it out to the bf, they give you the good thick TP!  One of the reasons why I decided to come to Gary Danko was because of the flexibility of the menu; after all I can be a picky eater at times!  Also, it's a plus that we didn't know about out til receiving the bill, valet is added to your check, they don't take the $11 payment at the front, so no need to stop by the ATM beforehand.

    Gary Danko we love you; thanks for putting the cherry on top to our Anniversary weekend!

    We flew into SF for my husband's and son's birthday. I planned a weekend of activities and hoped to get Gary Danko, but they were booked. We lucked out while at our friend's house for Thanksgiving as a 9pm reservation became available for that Saturday. I booked and later added the special occasion info on Saturday afternoon.
    I actually think the price was a good deal for the quality of the food. We ordered seared foie gras, seared scallops, lobster with mash potatoes, seafood curry, lemon duck breast, steak filet, chocolate soufflé, and ice cream macaroons.
    Everything was good. The dishes I probably wouldn't order again as they didn't stand out to me were the seared foie gras (served without toast; we prefer a fruit sauce with toast without the caramelized onions; but the quality of the foie gras itself was very good), the seared scallops (nothing you can't get elsewhere), and the duck (tender but I prefer a crispier skin; the flavor reminded me a little of Thanksgiving turkey and stuffing). The dishes we really liked that were more extraordinary were the lobster and mash potato and the seafood curry (doesn't taste at all like Asian curry; just a light creamy taste). The chocolate soufflé (very light in our case unlike another review) which we added vanilla ice cream to was the best I've ever had.
    Our down to earth server (aware of asking me if I wanted to exclude the blue cheese butter for my 7yo daughter's filet) was excellent. The auxiliary staff were a bit unfriendly (no smiles even) and stuffy...probably because we brought our 2 kids.
    Except for making us feel a little like we were in a Pretty Woman movie because of our kids (we eat in fine dining restaurants enough where my kids love foie gras and can distinguish the difference between different qualities of steak), we enjoyed our dining experience and would return the next time we are in town. However, I was a bit sad that they didn't do anything special for my husband and son's birthdays, but I left it alone especially since we had a lot of sweets already and felt awkward to ask in front of them.

    1/28/2014

    One of the most enjoyable dining experiences I've ever had.

    I got a reservation for my parents and I to celebrate my mother's birthday. I called 2 months in advance to get a 6pm reservation time on a Monday. If you want to get a more "dinner" dining time, then I suggest calling right when you can start making reservations, which is two months prior. The first time I called, I was only offered a 9pm time slot.

    For the food: the portions here are huge for a tasting menu! We each got the 4-course. I was debating between 4 vs. 5 courses and I am so glad that I chose the 4-course. Be aware that the food is very, very rich. You will leave feeling stuffed. I will be honest in saying that nothing about the food is revolutionary -- there's no innovative pairing of flavors or ingredients. The food is more of "classic" fine dining, meaning that you should not expect molecular gastronomy types of things; it's more of meat and potatoes, fish, and cream sauces (hence the heavy feeling after). However, all of it is prepared very well.

    Service is also excellent here. Water is always refilled, and the waitstaff is attentive at just the right moments. All the little details are attended to, and there is no judgment about how many courses you decide to order.

    Overpriced? Definitely. This isn't a place that you come to for a great value. But, solid food + excellent service makes this a place that should be visited to celebrate a special occasion.

    Tip: not everyone at the table has to order the same amount of courses. This was something that I was wondering about as I was reading up on this place! Also, valet is the cheapest option ($12, I believe), unless you're lucky enough to find street parking.   It's right next Ghiradelli square.

    2/13/2014

    Gary Danko, how are you rated the best restaurant in SF by Yelpers?!

    I've been to Manresa, Saison, Coi, Benu, Meadowood, Keiko a Nob Hill, Cyrus, Quince, Boulevard, Commis, the list goes on and on...but this meal by far was the most uninteresting.

    What shocked us the minute we were seated at the table was how crowded it felt inside. The over sized cheese cart kept bumping into my friend's chair during dinner. You would expect a restaurant of this caliber to give their guests more privacy and space.

    The food was lacking in character, creativity and quality. The scallop risotto was average. The steak was dry and not very flavorful. Harris' Restaurant definitely has better quality meats. Some of the dishes were too salty.

    The cheese course which is usually extra was marginal. They didn't have a good cheese selection as compared to other high end restaurants. It was abundant but not exciting. I felt sorry for our server because he sounded like a broken record trying to recite the two dozen or so cheese options on the cart. That's a tough job. The cart was sitting in the room for most of the evening. Some of the cheeses tasted lukewarm and softer than normal.

    The wine pairing wasn't necessary. I didn't think it enhanced the food. Or maybe the food didn't compliment the wine. I'm going to go out on a limb to say the wine was better than the food that evening.

    In terms of pricing, it is one of the more reasonable tasting menus offered in the Bay Area. You definitely feel full after you leave the restaurant. I can understand why a lot of men like this place. They can make their dates happy and also feel like they're not eating foam.

    I feel like Gary Danko caters to diners who enjoy quantity of portions, flexibility with course selection and good service. Yes, the service was the star of the evening. We enjoyed the experience because our servers were attentive and excellent.

    I won't be returning unless someone special requests a meal there. I have several friends who love it there. I guess it's hard to please everyone all the time.
